\begin_layout Section*
The 
\series bold
Fréchet
\series default
 derivative: a robust standard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start our series with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

canonical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 definition of a derivative in higher dimensions.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is said to have a 
\series bold
Fréchet
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
F-
\series default
) 
\series bold
derivative
\series default
 
\series bold
at 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for a given norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 if there exists a (unique) linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, called the F-derivative, that satisfies the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\alpha)\qquad\lim_{\Delta\to0}\frac{\left\Vert f(x+\Delta)-\left[f(x)+{\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)\right]\right\Vert }{\|\Delta\|}=0
\]

\end_inset

where the limit is taken over all subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Delta_{n}\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 tending to zero.
 Notice that this is a natural generalization of the one-dimensional case
 where we replace absolute value errors with norm errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before giving more definitions, let us discuss some nuances and implications
 of the above definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general, the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 is non-constructive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 is linear in its 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 parameter, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{\lambda(f_{1}+f_{2})}=\lambda({\cal A}_{x}^{f_{1}}+{\cal A}_{x}^{f_{2}})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the one-dimensional case (
\begin_inset Formula $n=m=1$
\end_inset

), the F-derivative and derivative coincide in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\delta)=\delta f'(x)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The F-derivative is independent of different choices of the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the fact that for two norms 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, there always exist constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}\geq c_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}\|x\|\leq\|x\|'\leq c_{2}\|x\|\quad\forall x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other works of literature, we might see the following variations and
 applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The definition in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 may be equivalently written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{y\to x}\frac{\left\Vert f(y)-\left[f(x)+{\cal A}_{x}^{f}(y-x)\right]\right\Vert }{\|y-x\|}=0
\]

\end_inset

where the limit is over all subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 going to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 (
\emph on
Prove this as a simple exercise
\emph default
!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

 may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $Df(x)[\Delta]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Df_{x}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)\Delta$
\end_inset

 to emphasize the dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In optimization theory, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)+{\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

 is often called the 
\series bold
first-order approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we have the above definition of a derivative, we can make the several
 follow-up definitions.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Fréchet
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
F-
\series default
)
\series bold
 differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if its F-derivative 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 Consequently, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Fréchet
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
F-
\series default
) 
\series bold
differentiable
\series default
 or has 
\series bold
Fréchet 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
F-
\series default
)
\series bold
 differentiability
\series default
 if it is F-differentiable at all points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some important properties that are unique to F-differentiability are as
 follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is F-differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
continuous
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\bar{x}\to x}f(\bar{x})=f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f(x)+{\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\Delta):\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a tangent plane of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, some important anti-properties of F-derivatives and F-differentiability
 are as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Delta_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
need not
\series default
 lie on a line, e.g., like in the definition of a 
\series bold
partial derivative
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f_{i}/\partial x_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In fact, the existence of the partial derivatives at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
is generally not
\series default
 sufficient to conclude F-differentiability at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Exercise
\emph default
.
 Consider the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\gamma_{1})\qquad f(x_{1},x_{2})=\begin{cases}
x_{1}, & \text{if }x_{2}=0,\\
x_{2}, & \text{if }x_{1}=0,\\
1, & \text{otherwise},
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

at zero.
 Show that the partial derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exist at zero, but the function itself is not F-differentiable.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
