\begin_layout Standard
Often, we do not need full F-differentiability of a multivariate function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to derive interesting results about 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Below, we describe a weaker notion of differentiability and its intriguing
 properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
The Gateaux derivative: provably weaker, but more flexible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next stop on our journey is a weaker, but related notion of a derivative.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is said to have a 
\series bold
Gateaux
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
G-
\series default
) 
\series bold
derivative
\series default
 
\series bold
at
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for a given norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 if there exists a (unique) linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}:\mathbb{R}_{+}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, called the G-derivative, that satisfies the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\beta)\qquad\lim_{t\downarrow0}\frac{\left\Vert f(x+t\Delta)-\left[f(x)+{\cal B}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)\right]\right\Vert }{t}=0\quad\forall\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

where the limit is taken over all positive subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{n}\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

 tending to zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like in the previous post, let us discuss a few nuances and implications
 of the above definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general, the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 is non-constructive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 is linear in its 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 parameter, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{\lambda(f_{1}+f_{2})}=\lambda({\cal B}_{x}^{f_{1}}+{\cal B}_{x}^{f_{2}})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compared to the F-derivative, the subsequences in the G-derivative are restricte
d to subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{n}d\}$
\end_inset

 which lie on a line emanating from the origin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the one-dimensional case (
\begin_inset Formula $n=m=1$
\end_inset

), the F-derivative and G-derivative coincide.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similar to the F-derivative, the G-derivative is independent of different
 choices of the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 (for the same reasons).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some works may have the same notation for the Fréchet and Gateaux derivatives,
 while others may prefer 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{x}f(x)[\Delta]$
\end_inset

 for Fréchet and 
\begin_inset Formula $Df(x)[\Delta]$
\end_inset

 for Gateaux.
 The two notions may be related as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has an F-derivative 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 then (i) it also has a G-derivative 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}={\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is convex, then the F-derivative 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 exists at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if and only if the G-derivative 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 exists at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now make the corresponding follow-up definitions.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Gateaux
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
G-
\series default
)
\series bold
 differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if its G-derivative 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 Consequently, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Gateaux
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
G-
\series default
) 
\series bold
differentiable
\series default
 or has 
\series bold
Gateaux 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
F-
\series default
)
\series bold
 differentiability
\series default
 if it is G-differentiable at all points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the above definitions in mind, we give a few properties that merely
 require G-differentiability (instead of F-differentiability).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is G-differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
hemicontinuous
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, i.e., for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\delta(\varepsilon,\Delta)$
\end_inset

 such that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\delta$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\|f(x+t\Delta)-f(x)\|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Exercise
\emph default
.
 Consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\gamma_{2})\qquad f(x_{1},x_{2})=\begin{cases}
0, & \text{if }x=0,\\
\dfrac{x_{2}(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2})^{3/2}}{(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2})^{2}+x_{2}^{2}}, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a G-derivative at zero, but not an F-derivative at zero.
 Show, moreover, that the G-derivative is hemicontinuous at zero.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is G-differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=x^{T}x$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then the partial derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exist at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

 is given by the 
\series bold
Jacobian
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal B}_{x}^{f}\equiv\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{\partial f_{1}}{\partial x_{1}}(x) & \cdots & \frac{\partial f_{1}}{\partial x_{m}}(x)\\
\vdots &  & \vdots\\
\frac{\partial f_{n}}{\partial x_{1}}(x) & \cdots & \frac{\partial f_{n}}{\partial x_{m}}(x)
\end{array}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times m};
\]

\end_inset

its transpose in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
, and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(x)\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
More general versions of the Jacobian and gradient exist for other inner
