 The (generalized) gradient is specifically defined as the unique element
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(x)\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times m}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle ({\cal B}_{x}^{f})^{*}\tau,\Delta\right\rangle =\left\langle \nabla f(x)\tau,\Delta\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $({\cal B}_{x}^{f})^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the adjoint operator of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
