\begin_layout Section*
Differentials: a useful, but naive surrogate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In one-dimensional calculus, students are typically introduced to the definition
 of the derivative of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by constructive means.
 Specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\theta)\qquad\lim_{t\downarrow0}\frac{f(x+t)-f(x)}{t}=\lim_{t\uparrow0}\frac{f(x+t)-f(x)}{t}=\lim_{t\to0}\frac{f(x+t)-f(x)}{t}=f'(x)
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 is called the (univariate) 
\series bold
derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 In this special setting, the existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 enjoys all the nice properties of the F-derivative (e.g., continuity and
 tangency) and G-derivative (e.g., chain rule) 
\emph on
without the issues of construction
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is then natural to ask whether 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta)$
\end_inset

 could be extended to the multivariate setting while simultaneously keeping
 (i) its constructive nature 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 (ii) the nice properties of the F-derivative (and G-derivative).
 Below, we show an approach of obtaining (i) which partially obtains (ii).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is said to have a 
\series bold
Gateaux 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
G-
\series default
) 
\series bold
differential
\series default
 
\series bold
at
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 if the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\pi_{1})\qquad V^{f}(x,\Delta)=\lim_{t\to0}\frac{f(x+t\Delta)-f(x)}{t},
\]

\end_inset

called the G-differential, is well-defined.
 Here, the limit is taken over all subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{n}\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 If, in addition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\pi_{2})\qquad\lim_{\Delta\to0}\frac{\|f(x+t\Delta)-f(x)-V^{f}(x,\Delta)\|}{\|\Delta\|}=0
\]

\end_inset

where the limit is taken over all subsequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Delta_{n}\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is also said to have a 
\series bold
Fréchet
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
F-
\series default
)
\series bold
 differential at 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (also denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(x,\Delta)$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now make a few glancing remarks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unlike the definitions of an F-derivative or G-derivative, the definition
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi_{1})$
\end_inset

 is constructive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similar to the one-dimensional case, the well-definedness of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(x,\Delta)$
\end_inset

 equivalent to the left and right limits (in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) being equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the one-dimensional case of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m=1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{f}(x,1)=f'(x)=-V^{f}(x,-1).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is straightforward to see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(x,\Delta)$
\end_inset

 exists for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(x,\Delta)={\cal B}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi_{2})$
\end_inset

 holds then 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(x,\Delta)={\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we have fulfilled property (i), the following anti-properties (given
 as exercises) show that property (ii) cannot be fully realized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Exercise
\emph default
.
 Consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x_{1},x_{2})=\begin{cases}
0, & \text{if }x=0,\\
\dfrac{x_{1}x_{2}^{2}}{x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{4}}, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(0,\Delta)$
\end_inset

 exists for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not have a G-derivative at zero.
 As a bonus, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x_{1},x_{2})={\rm sgn}(x_{2})\min(|x_{1}|,|x_{2}|)
\]

\end_inset

which is clearly continuous at zero.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(0,\Delta)$
\end_inset

 exists for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not have a G-derivative at zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the nice property about the G-differential (resp.
 F-differential) is that it gives a good initial estimate for the G-derivative
 (or F-derivative) if one can extract the appropriate linear form from it
 (and verify property 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi_{2})$
\end_inset

 in the case of the F-derivative) or we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is G-differentiable (resp.
 F-differentiable).
 A classic example of the utility of the differential is in deriving the
 derivative of the log determinant of a matrix, which we show below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:{\cal S}_{++}^{n}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(M)=\log\det M$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal S}_{++}^{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes the space of positive definite matrices.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{++}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(M)=\det(M)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial function of the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (and, hence differentiable) we can obtain the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by differentials and the chain rule.
 Using some standard linear algebra techniques, the F-differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 (and, hence, the F-derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

) is then given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V^{h}(M,\Delta) & =\lim_{t\to0}\frac{\det(M+t\Delta)-\det(M)}{t}\\
 & =\lim_{t\to0}\frac{\det(M[I+tM^{-1}\Delta])-\det(M)}{t}\\
 & =\det(M)\lim_{t\to0}\frac{\det(I+tM^{-1}\Delta)-1}{t}\\
 & =\det(M){\rm tr}(M^{-1}\Delta)={\cal A}_{M}^{h}(\Delta),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence, by the chain rule, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal A}_{M}^{f}(\Delta)={\cal A}_{\det M}^{\log(\cdot)}{\cal {\cal A}}_{M}^{h}(\Delta)=\frac{\det(M){\rm tr}(M^{-1}\Delta)}{\det(M)}={\rm tr}(M^{-1}\Delta).
\]

\end_inset

One can even obtain the gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(x)=M^{-T}$
\end_inset

 by using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal A}_{M}^{f}(\Delta)={\rm tr}(M^{-1}\Delta)=\left\langle M^{-T},\Delta\right\rangle .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To close, let us present this nice schematic of the various relations between
 G/F-derivatives and G/F-differentials in terms of the displacement variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 that shows up in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal B}_{x}^{f}(\Delta)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{f}(x,\Delta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

